{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"eaea157f-74e7-4f66-b86a-ba070a491a19","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. You create a custom `Window` subclass and override the corresponding methods:\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (`Window`) |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart` | `OnCreated` |\n| `OnSleep` | `OnStopped` |\n| `OnResume` | `OnResumed` |\n\n**Example:**\n\n```csharp\n// CustomWindow.cs\npublic class CustomWindow : Window\n{\n    public CustomWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()\n    {\n        base.OnCreated();\n        // Previously OnStart\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnStopped()\n    {\n        base.OnStopped();\n        // Previously OnSleep\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnResumed()\n    {\n        base.OnResumed();\n        // Previously OnResume\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThen in your `App.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    return new CustomWindow(new MainPage());\n}\n```\n\nYou also get additional granularity with `OnActivated`, `OnDeactivated`, and `OnDestroying` if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5d10baad-4249-49c3-90c9-13103b371208","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. You use the `Window` lifecycle events or configure platform-specific lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`. The `Application` class in MAUI still has `OnStart`... wait, let me think carefully.\n\nActually, in .NET MAUI, the `Application` class no longer has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` virtual methods. \n\nInstead, MAUI moved to a `Window`-based lifecycle model where you override methods like `OnCreated`, `OnActivated`, `OnDeactivated`, `OnStopped`, and `OnResumed` by creating a custom `Window` subclass and returning it from `Application.CreateWindow`. The old Xamarin.Forms lifecycle events roughly map to these new window events.","outputTokens":721,"requestId":"F406:CA693:1E6C55B:22407E9:69E81A87"},"id":"12965167-e144-4d04-8613-a9a6b08d202e","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:47:17.634Z","parentId":"9a9a92d9-6941-4f13-9d87-0fbb556a36cb"}
